html.body: ONTOX_LB0003_001 Autophagy pathway Autophagy (or autophagocytosis) is the natural, conserved degradation of the cell that removes unnecessary or dysfunctional components through a lysosome-dependent regulated mechanism. It allows the orderly degradation and recycling of cellular components. Although initially characterized as a primordial degradation pathway induced to protect against starvation, it has become increasingly clear that autophagy also plays a major role in the homeostasis of non-starved cells. Defects in autophagy have been linked to various human diseases, including neurodegeneration and cancer, and interest in modulating autophagy as a potential treatment for these diseases has grown rapidly.(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Autophagy). This pathway was constructed based on the Autophagy pathway available on the Parkinsons Disease Map (https://pdmap.uni.lu/minerva/) and the Wikipathways WP4923 (https://www.wikipathways.org/index.php/Pathway:WP4923). Additional information was incorporated based on the literature. All edges were annotated with the correspondent sources. Name: exocyst A protein complex peripherally associated with the plasma membrane that determines where vesicles dock and fuse. At least eight complex components are conserved between yeast and mammals. Two different variants are catalogued on the ComplexPortal. Exocyst, EXOC6 variant ComplexAc: CPX-4943 Homo sapiens; 9606 Exocyst, EXOC6B variant ComplexAc: CPX-4944 Homo sapiens; 9606 Recruited to sites of active exocytosis and membrane expansion, where it mediates the tethering of secretory vesicles to the plasma membrane in preparation for soluble N-ethylmaleimide-sensitive factor (NSF) attachment protein receptor (SNARE)-mediated membrane fusion. The targeting of secretory vesicles to the plasma membrane involves direct interactions of the Exocyst with PI(4,5)P2. In addition, a number of small GTP-binding proteins interact with components of the exocyst and regulate the assembly, localization, and function of this complex. The Exocyst participates in a number of biological processes such as ciliogenesis, migration, autophagy, trafficking and cytokinesis. https://www.ebi.ac.uk/complexportal/complex/CPX-4943 https://www.ebi.ac.uk/complexportal/complex/CPX-4944
